    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Acomastylis humilis improperly include inducing vomiting, which can lead to dehydration and electrolyte imbalance. Experiencing nausea and causing diarrhea are also possible, as the plant's toxic compounds can irritate the gastrointestinal tract. Furthermore, improper use of Acomastylis humilis may trigger allergic reactions, including skin irritation, respiratory issues, and anaphylaxis in severe cases. This is because the plant contains sesquiterpene lactones, which can cause an immune response in some individuals. These side effects occur due to the plant's toxic compounds, which can interact with the body's systems and cause adverse reactions.",
    "uses": "Acomastylis humilis, also known as dwarf or rock astilbe, has been used in traditional medicine for various purposes. Its roots, leaves, and stems are believed to possess antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties. In traditional medicine, Acomastylis humilis has been used to treat various ailments, including fever, sore throats, and skin conditions. However, further research is needed to confirm its effectiveness and potential side effects. Traditional healers have also used Acomastylis humilis to make teas and infusions for medicinal purposes.",
    "taxonomy": "Acomastylis humilis is classified as a member of the plant family Saxifragaceae, commonly known as the saxifrage or crassulacean families, and more specifically, it belongs to the genus Acomastylis. It is a type of flowering plant native to the mountainous regions of New Zealand. The Acomastylis genus is closely related to the saxifrage family, Saxifragaceae, which includes a diverse range of plants. Acomastylis humilis is one of the several species within this genus, characterized by its unique features and adaptations to its native habitat. Further classification of Acomastylis humilis can be understood within the context of its phylogenetic relationships and the evolutionary history of the Saxifragaceae family.",
    "benefits": "Acomastylis humilis, a flowering plant species, has been studied for its potential health benefits due to its unique bioactive compounds. Research suggests that extracts from this plant may possess antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties, which could aid in wound healing and alleviate symptoms of certain diseases. The antioxidants present in Acomastylis humilis may also play a role in protecting against cell damage and oxidative stress. Further studies are needed to confirm the efficacy of Acomastylis humilis in treating various health conditions. The potential benefits of this plant make it an area of interest for future research and development.",
    "parts": "Acomastylis humilis, a plant native to New Zealand, has been studied for its potential medicinal properties. However, limited information is available on its specific medicinal parts. The plant is part of the Proteaceae family, which is known for containing compounds with potential health benefits. Further research is needed to determine the specific medicinal parts of Acomastylis humilis and its potential uses. More studies are required to fully understand the plant's medicinal properties and its potential applications in traditional or modern medicine.",
    "intro": "Acomastylis humilis, commonly known as the Mountain Sandwort, is a low-growing, mat-forming perennial plant native to the mountainous regions of New Zealand. The health benefits of Acomastylis humilis include its potential anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties, which may help to soothe skin irritations and support the immune system. Bioactive constituents of this plant include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and saponins, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. Acomastylis humilis is typically used in herbal preparations such as teas, tinctures, and infusions, often combined with other herbs to support skin health and well-being."
